The database zoo: why purpose-built instead of relational.

You've already met relational databases, on R-D-S and Aurora. They're extraordinarily general: almost any data shape can be coaxed into rows and columns, and S-Q-L can express almost any query. So why does AWS publish a whole zoo of other databases? Because at scale, generality has a cost. A relational engine handling petabyte-scale analytics, microsecond key-value lookups, graph traversal across a billion edges, or time-series sensor data will be slower and more expensive than a database purpose-built for that shape. Each service here answers one specific access pattern brilliantly, and almost everything else badly. The skill is recognising which cue points at which service.

There are two anchors. DynamoDB is AWS's serverless NoSQL database, a key-value and document store that delivers single-digit-millisecond reads and writes at any scale, with no servers to manage, no schema to define upfront, and automatic replication across three availability zones. It underpins most serverless architectures on AWS. Redshift is AWS's data warehouse: a columnar, massively-parallel store built for analytical queries over terabytes to petabytes of data.

Around the two of them sit a handful of purpose-built databases, like Neptune, DocumentDB, Keyspaces, Timestream, MemoryDB, and Q-L-D-B, plus an analytics stack on top of S3: Athena, Glue, E-M-R, and OpenSearch. This module walks DynamoDB in depth, then Redshift and the analytics stack, then the rest of the zoo, and closes with a cue-to-service cheat sheet.
